Problem

You are given an array prices[] where prices[i] represents the price of a stock on the ith day.

Find the maximum profit you can achieve by choosing one day to buy and one future day to sell the stock.

If no profit is possible, return 0.

Example

Input

prices = [7,1,5,3,6,4]

Output

5

Explanation
Buy on day 2 (price = 1)
Sell on day 5 (price = 6)

Profit = 6 - 1 = 5

Intuition

To maximize profit:

Buy at the lowest price seen so far

Sell when you find a higher price later

So while traversing the array:

Track the minimum price

Compute possible profit

Update maximum profit

Approach (Single Pass / Greedy)
Steps

Initialize

minPrice = prices[0]

maxProfit = 0

Traverse the array

Update the minimum price

Calculate profit

Update maximum profit


Java Implementation
class Solution {
    public int maxProfit(int[] prices) {
        
        int minPrice = prices[0];
        int maxProfit = 0;

        for(int i = 1; i < prices.length; i++) {
            
            if(prices[i] < minPrice) {
                minPrice = prices[i];
            }

            int profit = prices[i] - minPrice;

            if(profit > maxProfit) {
                maxProfit = profit;
            }
        }

        return maxProfit;
    }
}
Complexity Analysis

Time Complexity

O(n)

Single traversal of the array.

Space Complexity

O(1)

Only variables used.

Pattern

This problem follows the Greedy + Minimum Tracking Pattern
